"# Chapter 1 — The Base

Every Scheme program is a shape. A parenthesis opens the shape, a parenthesis closes it. Inside sit atoms and other shapes. That is the entire syntax. If you know how to open and close a parenthesis, you already speak Scheme's grammar.

Motoi's base library is small. Six or seven verbs get you almost everywhere: `cons` to glue two things together, `car` to take the first, `cdr` to take the rest, `list` to make a shape from atoms, `define` to name something, `lambda` to make a function, `if` to choose between two paths. Everything else in this book stacks on top of those.

I am going to walk you from nothing to something four times in this chapter. The first walk is thirty seconds long. The last walk assembles a tiny language of your own that adds two numbers written in words. If you have never seen Scheme before, that last one will feel like a trick. It is not a trick. It is what happens when small verbs compose.

## Why this lib exists

There are two reasons to make the base language so small.

The first is honesty. If the language is small, you can read all of it in an afternoon and know what you have. There is no hidden shelf where the real magic lives. When your program surprises you, the surprise is in your logic, not in a runtime you did not know existed.

The second is composition. A small kit of verbs that combine cleanly beats a large kit of verbs that overlap. `cons`, `car`, `cdr` are three verbs that between them let you build any tree, any list, any record, any table. You do not need special syntax for arrays; you have lists. You do not need special syntax for structs; you have named tuples made of `cons` cells. One shape, applied everywhere.

## Problem 1 — Say hello

Nothing to something in three lines. Motoi has a verb called `display` that prints a value to the terminal.

```
(display \"hello, world\")
;; => hello, world
```

That is a whole program. Save it to `hello.scm`, run `bin/motoi hello.scm`, and the terminal prints `hello, world`. You have made the computer say something. This is the smallest useful program.

Notice the two things sitting next to each other inside the parentheses. `display` is a verb — a function. `\"hello, world\"` is a value — a string. When Motoi sees a shape whose first atom is a verb, it evaluates the verb with the rest of the shape as arguments. That is the whole rule.

## Problem 2 — Add two numbers, name the answer

Now let us name something. Every real program names things.

```
(define greeting \"hello, world\")
(define answer (+ 40 2))
(display greeting)
(display \" — the answer is: \")
(display answer)
;; => hello, world — the answer is: 42
```

`define` takes a name and a value and binds them. From then on, that name means that value. `(+ 40 2)` is a shape whose first atom is a verb (`+`) that takes numbers and returns their sum. The value `42` is what `answer` remembers.

We stacked three `display` calls. Order matters — Motoi runs the lines top to bottom. If you swap `greeting` and `answer`, you will see the numbers first and the greeting second. The kid experiment: swap them, run it, see what changes.

## Problem 3 — A list of your favorite colors, printed one by one

The trick here: we build a list, then walk it. Two new verbs (`list` and `for-each`) and one built-in shape (the list itself).

```
(define favorites (list \"pink\" \"green\" \"brown\"))

(for-each (lambda (color)
            (display color)
            (display \"\\n\"))
          favorites)
;; => pink
;;    green
;;    brown
```

Read that shape slowly. `favorites` is a list of three strings. `for-each` is a verb that takes a function and a list. It calls the function once for each element, in order.

The function itself is a `lambda` — a nameless mini-function. `(lambda (color) ...)` says: I am a function that takes one argument called `color`; when you call me, I display the color and then a newline.

You just wrote a loop without writing a `for`. That is a loop expressed as composition: `for-each` accepts a function, and the function does the per-element work. Everywhere in this book, when you want a loop, you will reach for something shaped like this.

## Problem 4 (pro) — Add two numbers written in words

Now the small language. We want `(add-words 'three 'four)` to return `7`.

```
(define digit-of
  (lambda (word)
    (cond ((eq? word 'zero)  0)
          ((eq? word 'one)   1)
          ((eq? word 'two)   2)
          ((eq? word 'three) 3)
          ((eq? word 'four)  4)
          ((eq? word 'five)  5)
          ((eq? word 'six)   6)
          ((eq? word 'seven) 7)
          ((eq? word 'eight) 8)
          ((eq? word 'nine)  9)
          (else 'unknown-word))))

(define add-words
  (lambda (a b)
    (let ((x (digit-of a))
          (y (digit-of b)))
      (if (or (eq? x 'unknown-word) (eq? y 'unknown-word))
          'unknown-word
          (+ x y)))))

(display (add-words 'three 'four))
;; => 7

(display (add-words 'nine 'nine))
;; => 18

(display (add-words 'banana 'four))
;; => unknown-word
```

Three new pieces: `cond` (chained if/else), `let` (temporary names inside an expression), and `eq?` (are two symbols the same). A symbol is an atom starting with a quote — `'three` means the symbol `three`.

Read the shape from the outside in. `add-words` takes two words. It looks each up with `digit-of`. If either lookup returned the marker `'unknown-word`, the whole call returns that marker; otherwise it returns the sum.

`digit-of` is a lookup table implemented with `cond`. Nothing hidden. The list of words is the entire vocabulary.

This is the shape of many Motoi programs: a small vocabulary of atoms, a lookup that turns atoms into meaning, and a combiner that produces an answer. From here it is a short walk to writing a mini-calculator, a Roman-numeral converter, or a tiny interpreter for your own language.

## Capstone — Build a list of the first five squares by hand

No `for-each` this time. Just `cons`, `list`, and `*`. This is the shape of a hand-built list:

```
(define first-five-squares
  (cons (* 1 1)
    (cons (* 2 2)
      (cons (* 3 3)
        (cons (* 4 4)
          (cons (* 5 5) '()))))))

(display first-five-squares)
;; => (1 4 9 16 25)
```

Read the nesting. `'()` is the empty list — the base case. Every `cons` glues one number onto the front of the list already built. That is a linked list, spelled out. In Chapter 2 you will meet `map` and never spell one out again. But it is good to have spelled it out once. When someone tells you a list is `cons` all the way down, you will know they meant it literally.

## What's next

You now have atoms, verbs, functions, lists, and choice. That is more than enough for one afternoon. In Chapter 2 we swap the hand-cranked `cons` chain for `map`, `filter`, and the pipe pattern — the shape that lets you say what you want the list to look like instead of how to build it.
")
